{"version": 1, "timestamp": 1772705906.3866744, "pages": [{"object": "page", "id": "2dc5964e-68a4-8008-89c8-f7f131f0b4ba", "created_time": "2026-01-02T09:28:00.000Z", "last_edited_time": "2026-03-05T09:56:00.000Z", "created_by": {"object": "user", "id": "b34a9a35-90e8-4993-b980-07875455ab51"}, "last_edited_by": {"object": "user", "id": "b34a9a35-90e8-4993-b980-07875455ab51"}, "cover": null, "icon": null, "parent": {"type": "database_id", "database_id": "2dc5964e-68a4-8090-9c4a-c1dc169b16fb"}, "archived": false, "in_trash": false, "is_locked": false, "properties": {"Subject": {"id": "FzC%3F", "type": "relation", "relation": [{"id": "952c1fb5-fa71-4426-a9c3-f4f6e6b0678f"}, {"id": "1695964e-68a4-80ec-a323-c625c1dcc59d"}], "has_more": false}, "Content": {"id": "bN%7DV", "type": "rich_text", "rich_text": []}, "Subtag": {"id": "~Esu", "type": "select", "select": {"id": "19d84af8-d99e-49ac-9a94-bfc6cbc43f5d", "name": "Clinical Features Management", "color": "yellow"}}, "Name": {"id": "title", "type": "title", "title": [{"type": "text", "text": {"content": "ACS Comparison Table", "link": null}, "annotations": {"bold": false, "italic": false, "strikethrough": false, "underline": false, "code": false, "color": "default"}, "plain_text": "ACS Comparison Table", "href": null}]}}, "url": "https://www.notion.so/ACS-Comparison-Table-2dc5964e68a4800889c8f7f131f0b4ba", "public_url": "https://malleuscm.notion.site/ACS-Comparison-Table-2dc5964e68a4800889c8f7f131f0b4ba", "_block_html": "<p>This is a simple list of items</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Item 1</li>\n<li>Item 2</li>\n<li>Item 3</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Here is some coloured text</p>\n<p>Here is some <u>more</u> intricately <strong>formatted text</strong></p>\n<p>And here is a table</p>\n<tr><td>Row 1</td><td>Item 1</td><td>Column 3</td></tr>\n<tr><td>2.1</td><td>2.2</td><td>2.3</td></tr>\n<tr><td>Bla</td><td>Bla</td><td>Blah</td></tr>\n<h1>Heading 1</h1>\n<h2>Heading 2</h2>"}, {"object": "page", "id": "2dc5964e-68a4-8061-ac41-e511bee0ebb2", "created_time": "2026-01-02T09:28:00.000Z", "last_edited_time": "2026-01-25T12:23:00.000Z", "created_by": {"object": "user", "id": "b34a9a35-90e8-4993-b980-07875455ab51"}, "last_edited_by": {"object": "user", "id": "b34a9a35-90e8-4993-b980-07875455ab51"}, "cover": null, "icon": null, "parent": {"type": "database_id", "database_id": "2dc5964e-68a4-8090-9c4a-c1dc169b16fb"}, "archived": false, "in_trash": false, "is_locked": false, "properties": {"Subject": {"id": "FzC%3F", "type": "relation", "relation": [{"id": "952c1fb5-fa71-4426-a9c3-f4f6e6b0678f"}], "has_more": false}, "Content": {"id": "bN%7DV", "type": "rich_text", "rich_text": [{"type": "text", "text": {"content": "STEMI Criteria", "link": null}, "annotations": {"bold": false, "italic": false, "strikethrough": false, "underline": false, "code": false, "color": "default"}, "plain_text": "STEMI Criteria", "href": null}]}, "Subtag": {"id": "~Esu", "type": "select", "select": {"id": "044ec6f8-6021-4a88-8b69-95a74a55f722", "name": "Diagnosis/Investigations", "color": "pink"}}, "Name": {"id": "title", "type": "title", "title": [{"type": "text", "text": {"content": "ACS ECG Changes", "link": null}, "annotations": {"bold": false, "italic": false, "strikethrough": false, "underline": false, "code": false, "color": "default"}, "plain_text": "ACS ECG Changes", "href": null}]}}, "url": "https://www.notion.so/ACS-ECG-Changes-2dc5964e68a48061ac41e511bee0ebb2", "public_url": "https://malleuscm.notion.site/ACS-ECG-Changes-2dc5964e68a48061ac41e511bee0ebb2"}, {"object": "page", "id": "2dc5964e-68a4-80dc-800d-e1c46588446a", "created_time": "2026-01-02T10:04:00.000Z", "last_edited_time": "2026-03-05T09:41:00.000Z", "created_by": {"object": "user", "id": "b34a9a35-90e8-4993-b980-07875455ab51"}, "last_edited_by": {"object": "user", "id": "b34a9a35-90e8-4993-b980-07875455ab51"}, "cover": null, "icon": null, "parent": {"type": "database_id", "database_id": "2dc5964e-68a4-8090-9c4a-c1dc169b16fb"}, "archived": false, "in_trash": false, "is_locked": false, "properties": {"Subject": {"id": "FzC%3F", "type": "relation", "relation": [{"id": "1905964e-68a4-80b3-affd-c845789497dd"}], "has_more": false}, "Content": {"id": "bN%7DV", "type": "rich_text", "rich_text": [{"type": "text", "text": {"content": "<span class=\"sync\" sid=\"1759357779111_2_3027\">\n<ul><li>Catatonia is not a discrete psychiatric condition but a phenomenon that can be seen in oth mood and psychotic disorders</li><li>Per DSM-V, three of the following needed to diagnose catatonia: stupor, catalepsy, waxy flexibility, mutism, negativism, posturing, mannerisms, stereotypy, agitation, grimacing, echolalia, and echopraxia</li></ul><div><table border=\"1\" style=\"border-collapse: collapse; border-width: 2px;\"><thead><tr><th colspan=\"2\" style=\"border-width: 2px; padding: 3px; text-align: center;\"><strong>Catatonia per DSM-V</strong></th></tr><tr><th style=\"border-width: 2px; padding: 3px; text-align: left;\"><strong>Sign</strong></th><th style=\"border-width: 2px; padding: 3px; text-align: left;\"><strong>Description</strong></th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td style=\"border-width: 2px; padding: 3px;\"><strong>Stupor</strong></td><td style=\"border-width: 2px; padding: 3px;\">No psychomotor activity; the person is unresponsive and does not interact with the environment.</td></tr><tr><td style=\"border-width: 2px; padding: 3px;\"><strong>Catalepsy</strong></td><td style=\"border-width: 2px; padding: 3px;\">Person maintains a posture placed by another, even against gravity.</td></tr><tr><td style=\"border-width: 2px; padding: 3px;\"><strong>Waxy Flexibility</strong></td><td style=\"border-width: 2px; padding: 3px;\">Slight resistance to movement when positioned by an examiner, as if the limbs were made of wax.</td></tr><tr><td style=\"border-width: 2px; padding: 3px;\"><strong>Mutism</strong></td><td style=\"border-width: 2px; padding: 3px;\">Very limited or complete absence of verbal response (not due to language impairment like aphasia).</td></tr><tr><td style=\"border-width: 2px; padding: 3px;\"><strong>Negativism</strong></td><td style=\"border-width: 2px; padding: 3px;\">Resistance to instructions or external stimuli, or no response at all, without any apparent reason.</td></tr><tr><td style=\"border-width: 2px; padding: 3px;\"><strong>Posturing</strong></td><td style=\"border-width: 2px; padding: 3px;\">Actively holding a rigid or unusual posture against gravity without external prompting.</td></tr><tr><td style=\"border-width: 2px; padding: 3px;\"><strong>Mannerism</strong></td><td style=\"border-width: 2px; padding: 3px;\">Odd or exaggerated performance of normal actions, often appearing theatrical or bizarre.</td></tr><tr><td style=\"border-width: 2px; padding: 3px;\"><strong>Stereotypy</strong></td><td style=\"border-width: 2px; padding: 3px;\">Repetitive, purposeless movements performed frequently (e.g., rocking, hand-flapping).</td></tr><tr><td style=\"border-width: 2px; padding: 3px;\"><strong>Agitation</strong></td><td style=\"border-width: 2px; padding: 3px;\">Excessive motor activity that is not caused or influenced by the surroundings.</td></tr><tr><td style=\"border-width: 2px; padding: 3px;\"><strong>Grimacing</strong></td><td style=\"border-width: 2px; padding: 3px;\">Repetitive or inappropriate facial expressions, such as twisted or exaggerated movements.</td></tr><tr><td style=\"border-width: 2px; padding: 3px;\"><strong>Echolalia</strong></td><td style=\"border-width: 2px; padding: 3px;\">Imitation or repetition of another person\u2019s spoken words.</td></tr><tr><td style=\"border-width: 2px; padding: 3px;\"><strong>Echopraxia</strong></td><td style=\"border-width: 2px; padding: 3px;\">Imitation of another person\u2019s movements or gestures.</td></tr><tr><td style=\"border-width: 2px; padding: 3px;\"><i>N.B.</i></td><td style=\"border-width: 2px; padding: 3px;\"><i>Bush-Francis scale also includes signs of automatic obedience, autonomic abnormalities and grasp reflex as indicative of catatonia.</i></td></tr></tbody></table></div><div>\u00a0</div><div><img alt=\"undefined\" src=\"3bd2e262127e064f43b3ac3aea55c495.webp\"><br><i><span style=\"font-size: 10pt;\"><i>Catatonic stupor, with features of catalepsy<br>Public domain</i></span></i></div>\n</span>", "link": null}, "annotations": {"bold": false, "italic": false, "strikethrough": false, "underline": false, "code": false, "color": "default"}, "plain_text": "<span class=\"sync\" sid=\"1759357779111_2_3027\">\n<ul><li>Catatonia is not a discrete psychiatric condition but a phenomenon that can be seen in oth mood and psychotic disorders</li><li>Per DSM-V, three of the following needed to diagnose catatonia: stupor, catalepsy, waxy flexibility, mutism, negativism, posturing, mannerisms, stereotypy, agitation, grimacing, echolalia, and echopraxia</li></ul><div><table border=\"1\" style=\"border-collapse: collapse; border-width: 2px;\"><thead><tr><th colspan=\"2\" style=\"border-width: 2px; padding: 3px; text-align: center;\"><strong>Catatonia per DSM-V</strong></th></tr><tr><th style=\"border-width: 2px; padding: 3px; text-align: left;\"><strong>Sign</strong></th><th style=\"border-width: 2px; padding: 3px; text-align: left;\"><strong>Description</strong></th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td style=\"border-width: 2px; padding: 3px;\"><strong>Stupor</strong></td><td style=\"border-width: 2px; padding: 3px;\">No psychomotor activity; the person is unresponsive and does not interact with the environment.</td></tr><tr><td style=\"border-width: 2px; padding: 3px;\"><strong>Catalepsy</strong></td><td style=\"border-width: 2px; padding: 3px;\">Person maintains a posture placed by another, even against gravity.</td></tr><tr><td style=\"border-width: 2px; padding: 3px;\"><strong>Waxy Flexibility</strong></td><td style=\"border-width: 2px; padding: 3px;\">Slight resistance to movement when positioned by an examiner, as if the limbs were made of wax.</td></tr><tr><td style=\"border-width: 2px; padding: 3px;\"><strong>Mutism</strong></td><td style=\"border-width: 2px; padding: 3px;\">Very limited or complete absence of verbal response (not due to language impairment like aphasia).</td></tr><tr><td style=\"border-width: 2px; padding: 3px;\"><strong>Negativism</strong></td><td style=\"border-width: 2px; padding: 3px;\">Resistance to instructions or external stimuli, or no response at all, without any apparent reason.</td></tr><tr><td style=\"border-width: 2px; padding: 3px;\"><strong>Posturing</strong></td><td style=\"border-width: 2px; padding: 3px;\">Actively holding a rigid or unusual posture against gravity without external prompting.</td></tr><tr><td style=\"border-width: 2px; padding: 3px;\"><strong>Mannerism</strong></td><td style=\"border-width: 2px; padding: 3px;\">Odd or exaggerated performance of normal actions, often appearing theatrical or bizarre.</td></tr><tr><td style=\"border-width: 2px; padding: 3px;\"><strong>Stereotypy</strong></td><td style=\"border-width: 2px; padding: 3px;\">Repetitive, purposeless movements performed frequently (e.g., rocking, hand-flapping).</td></tr><tr><td style=\"border-width: 2px; padding: 3px;\"><strong>Agitation</strong></td><td style=\"border-width: 2px; padding: 3px;\">Excessive motor activity that is not caused or influenced by the surroundings.</td></tr><tr><td style=\"border-width: 2px; padding: 3px;\"><strong>Grimacing</strong></td><td style=\"border-width: 2px; padding: 3px;\">Repetitive or inappropriate facial expressions, such as twisted or exaggerated movements.</td></tr><tr><td style=\"border-width: 2px; padding: 3px;\"><strong>Echolalia</strong></td><td style=\"border-width: 2px; padding: 3px;\">Imitation or repetition of another person\u2019s spoken words.</td></tr><tr><td style=\"border-width: 2px; padding: 3px;\"><strong>Echopraxia</strong></td><td style=\"border-width: 2px; padding: 3px;\">Imitation of another person\u2019s movements or gestures.</td></tr><tr><td style=\"border-width: 2px; padding: 3px;\"><i>N.B.</i></td><td style=\"border-width: 2px; padding: 3px;\"><i>Bush-Francis scale also includes signs of automatic obedience, autonomic abnormalities and grasp reflex as indicative of catatonia.</i></td></tr></tbody></table></div><div>\u00a0</div><div><img alt=\"undefined\" src=\"3bd2e262127e064f43b3ac3aea55c495.webp\"><br><i><span style=\"font-size: 10pt;\"><i>Catatonic stupor, with features of catalepsy<br>Public domain</i></span></i></div>\n</span>", "href": null}]}, "Subtag": {"id": "~Esu", "type": "select", "select": {"id": "14dacdfa-ab02-4c98-adc2-9fd9068b0a31", "name": "Clinical Features", "color": "default"}}, "Name": {"id": "title", "type": "title", "title": [{"type": "text", "text": {"content": "Catatonia Clinical Features", "link": null}, "annotations": {"bold": false, "italic": false, "strikethrough": false, "underline": false, "code": false, "color": "default"}, "plain_text": "Catatonia Clinical Features", "href": null}]}}, "url": "https://www.notion.so/Catatonia-Clinical-Features-2dc5964e68a480dc800de1c46588446a", "public_url": "https://malleuscm.notion.site/Catatonia-Clinical-Features-2dc5964e68a480dc800de1c46588446a"}]}